    "body": "Implement minimal substrate for lifecycle tracking of long-running operations via pull-based querying. No callbacks, no async abstraction, no policy; designed to underpin LSP and job cancellation in follow-up work.\n\nSubstrate primitives:\n- vim.op.start { title = \"...\" } creates operation in running state\n- vim.op.list() returns snapshot of active operations\n- Per-operation accessors: state(), progress(), result(), error(), cancel(), finish()\n- Idempotent state machine: OP_RUNNING â†’ {OP_FINISHED|OP_CANCELED|OP_FAILED}\n- Registry discipline: only active operations stored; terminal ops auto-removed\n- Ownership: Operation objects fully owned by substrate; proper cleanup in op_release()\n\nTests (28 unit tests):\n- Lifecycle and idempotence\n- Progress semantics (optional, [0, 1], clamped)\n- Registry snapshotting\n- Terminal state transitions\n\nDeferred (follow-up PRs):\n- LSP integration (progress reporting, cancellation)\n- Job integration (background operation tracking)\n- UI overlay / progress indication\n- Event notifications\n\nMaintainer Notes:\n- Changes are confined to new API surface; zero impact on existing code\n- Lua bindings via standard FFI pattern; compatible with Neovim binding layer\n- All Object ownership accounted for (properly freed in op_release)\n- Idempotent transitions prevent subtle state-change bugs\n",
